The '''[[Seventh-day Adventist Church|Seventh-day Adventist]] educational system''' is the second-largest [[Christian school]] system in the world, after the Roman Catholic system (see [[Catholic school]]).{{Citation needed|date=April 2010}}
It has a total of 7,598 educational institutions operating in over 100 countries around the world with over 1.5 million students world-wide.<ref>http://education.gc.adventist.org/about.html</ref>
The denominationally-based school system began in the 1870s.<ref name="Education">[http://www.adventist.org/mission_and_service/education.html.en Education] on the church's official website</ref> The church supports [[holistic education]]: :"Mental, physical, social, and spiritual health, intellectual growth, and service to humanity form a core of values that are essential aspects of the Adventist education philosophy."<ref name="Education"/>
The ''[[Journal of Adventist Education]]'' (JAE) is published.
In 2009, [[Heather Knight (educator)|Heather Knight]], who received her doctorate from [[Stanford University]] and completed post-doctoral studies at [[Harvard University]], became the first [[African-American]] woman to lead an Adventist College in [[North American Division of Seventh-day Adventists|North America]] when she took over as [[President of Pacific Union College|President]] of [[Pacific Union College]].
== Education by level == === Primary === === Secondary === === Tertiary === {{See also|Seventh-day Adventist tertiary student ministry}}
== Education by area == === North America === The [[North American Division of Seventh-day Adventists|North American Division]] [http://nadeducation.org Office of Education] oversees 1049 schools with 65,000 students in the [[United States]], [[Canada]], and [[Bermuda]].
=== Asia === In some Asian countries, Adventist schools are referred to as "Sam Yuk" ([[Yue Chinese|Cantonese]]), "Samyuk" ([[Korean language|Korean]]), "San iku" ([[Japanese language|Japanese]]), or similar, meaning literally "three-bodied". This refers to a [[holistic education]] involving the three components of ''mind'', ''body'' and ''spirit/soul''. Contemporary approaches commonly include a fourth component, ''social''.{{fact|date=October 2007}}
